<div class=titlebar><table class=glow>
<a href=https://web.archive.org/20011101000000/http://www.irfanview.com/ target=_blank>Irfanview</a>
</table></div>

<div class=itemtext>
An image viewer and converter that supports tons of formats, even multimedia - you can play video and music files with it too.  It's loaded with features:
<li> Image Graphical Effects, Copy, Paste, Crop, Resize
<li> Convert animations to individual pictures
<li> Batch conversion, renaming, resizing, and recoloring of entire directories or lists of iimages
<li> Palette Control<p>
</div><div class=titlebar><table class=glow>
<a href=https://web.archive.org/20011101000000/http://www.notetab.com/ target=_blank>NoteTab</a>
</table></div>

<div class=itemtext>
This is the ULTIMATE text editor.  Anyone who writes HTML, scripts, or real programs must download this now.  The basic NoteTab Light is freeware, while commercial versions add even more features.
<li> Convert text lines to HTML (automatic &lt&;p&gt; and &lt&;br&gt;)
<li> Open links, delete tags, preview in browser
<li> Set text case, justify, block select
<li> Clips (imagine the text equivalent to browser javascript) that automatically format your text with wizards, fill in html with the attributes you want, launch programs, convert text, and more.  You can even write your own clips.
<li> NoteTab's ULTIMATE feature - multi-line search and replace.  You can even use reguler expressions.  You can do the search across multiple files too.
<li> An outline format that stores multiple documents of text as a single file.  You can select each page from an outline menu and hyperlinks are supported.  Outline files are read-only in the free version of NoteTab.
<li> Document statistics and TONS of options
<li> Customizable toolbar
<li> Integration with a spell checker, thesaurus, and HTML Tidy<p>
</div><div class=titlebar><table class=glow>
<a href=https://web.archive.org/20011101000000/http://www.iglyph.com/ target=_blank>TrayMenu</a>
</table></div>

<div class=itemtext>
This is a great shell improvement that adds a menu to your tray (with the time and volume control icons).  You can customize the menu in a ton of ways, like separators, icon size, sorting, etc.  There's a desktop control that lets you access a ton of options, and a windowlist for hiding/showing windows.  But the best feature is that you can create menus with shortcuts to directories so that you can get to files in your frequently-accessed folders from a menu.  You can even explore the entire My Computer directory structure with a shortcut to My Computer.<p>
</div><!end of sections>

